{"status":"success","result":"Okay, now I've got the full picture. This is genuinely well-designed. Here's what I'm seeing:\n\n*How routing actually works today:*\n• Regex patterns on the message upfront: `CODING_PATTERN` → Coder, has images → Artist, else → qwen3.5:35b\n• `shouldThink()` decides whether to flip on thinking mode\n• `AUTO_ESCALATE_PATTERN` catches when the model is struggling mid-response (apologies, \"I wasn't able to\", \"I'm stuck\") and escalates automatically\n• Jarvis also has explicit `escalate` and `ollama_generate` tools he can call himself\n\n*The gap you're describing:*\nThe current setup is mostly *reactive* — escalation happens after failure signals. The regex routing is proactive but brittle (regex can't catch intent ambiguity). Jarvis isn't making a *judgment call*, he's just pattern-matched and then either succeeds or fails up the ladder.\n\n*What's missing:* Jarvis doesn't yet have a strong internal voice that says \"hmm, this feels like it needs the Analyst before I even try.\" He mostly discovers that after struggling.\n\n*One concrete idea:*\nA lightweight pre-flight check — before Jarvis responds, he could do a quick `ollama_generate` to the Secretary (qwen3:4b) asking \"does this task need thinking mode, a specialist, or is it straightforward?\" Cheap, fast, and gives Jarvis a second opinion on routing before committing.\n\nIs that the kind of gap you're trying to close? Or is the bigger issue that Jarvis *knows* when to escalate but doesn't pull the trigger?","newSessionId":"9ab085a0-060d-41ae-b3d8-a97f4d571171"}
